10
00:00:48,830 --> 00:00:55,770
We discussed about Chicago School of Sociology in the 1920s and 1930s.

11
00:00:55,770 --> 00:00:59,870
They tried to analyze Chicago as a sociological laboratory.

12
00:00:59,870 --> 00:01:06,030
And they defined the city as a state of mind and body

13
00:01:06,030 --> 00:01:15,260
of customs and traditions, and of organized attitude and sentiment.

14
00:01:15,260 --> 00:01:21,280
So they tried to combine or integrate the relationship between the people,

15
00:01:21,280 --> 00:01:29,840
population concentration and cultural style, or cultural structure.

16
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:34,200
So they used the anthropological approaches to the cities

17
00:01:34,200 --> 00:01:40,800
and they did many ethnographic research on urban migrants and dwellers

18
00:01:40,800 --> 00:01:43,620
in metropolitan city.

19
00:01:43,620 --> 00:01:50,250
After the Chicago School, many sociologists and anthropologists

20
00:01:50,250 --> 00:01:55,230
focused on the urban community, especially migrant community

21
00:01:55,230 --> 00:01:57,080
in big metropolis.

22
00:01:57,080 --> 00:02:02,290
William F. White, Hervert Gans, and Elijah Anderson,

23
00:02:02,290 --> 00:02:05,790
all of these anthropologists and sociologists

24
00:02:05,790 --> 00:02:14,590
wrote a fascinating ethnography on these villages, or on these communities.

25
00:02:14,590 --> 00:02:19,290
But on the other hand, some of the other sociologists

26
00:02:19,290 --> 00:02:25,170
theorized the relationship, especially visualizing relationship in the people,

27
00:02:25,170 --> 00:02:26,770
in the city.

28
00:02:26,770 --> 00:02:36,850
In case of Howard Becker, he emphasized that the deviant behavior

29
00:02:36,850 --> 00:02:42,530
emerged or created by labeling process.

30
00:02:42,530 --> 00:02:51,160
So if you're labeled as deviant you tend to be deviant from yourself.

31
00:02:51,160 --> 00:02:55,800
But at the same time Erving Goffman, in his writing,

32
00:02:55,800 --> 00:03:01,930
he also analyzed the social performances by stigmatized people.

33
00:03:01,930 --> 00:03:08,110
So from Goffman's perspective, city is a kind of theater of gazing.

34
00:03:08,110 --> 00:03:15,700
Gazed and gazing, or labeled and labeling.

35
00:03:15,700 --> 00:03:20,419
But Chicago School focused on the city, especially related

36
00:03:20,419 --> 00:03:21,460
to the industrialization.

37
00:03:21,460 --> 00:03:24,090


38
00:03:24,090 --> 00:03:28,280
After the late 19th century and especially 20th century,

39
00:03:28,280 --> 00:03:33,280
the process of industrialization and immigrant movement

40
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:37,560
expanded in European countries and the U.S. So Chicago

41
00:03:37,560 --> 00:03:45,860
was the representative metropolis which integrated, or accepted

42
00:03:45,860 --> 00:03:49,880
the huge number of the migrants and immigrants.

43
00:03:49,880 --> 00:03:53,150
So the research by Chicago School was strongly

44
00:03:53,150 --> 00:03:57,950
influenced by this industrialization process.

45
00:03:57,950 --> 00:04:04,500
But as I already emphasized the history of a city and history of urbanization

46
00:04:04,500 --> 00:04:08,420
is much longer than history of industrialization.

47
00:04:08,420 --> 00:04:12,600
So some of the historian discussed about the history

48
00:04:12,600 --> 00:04:17,329
of the city and the urbanization before industrialization.

49
00:04:17,329 --> 00:04:23,410
Henri Pirenne is representative because he discussed medieval cities.

50
00:04:23,410 --> 00:04:27,750
Medieval cities with merchants and artisans.

51
00:04:27,750 --> 00:04:30,070
And networks of travelers.

52
00:04:30,070 --> 00:04:33,090
And freedom in the city.

53
00:04:33,090 --> 00:04:36,990
All of these characteristics in Medieval cities

54
00:04:36,990 --> 00:04:42,610
was very different from the characteristics in industrial city

55
00:04:42,610 --> 00:04:45,480
in modern times.

56
00:04:45,480 --> 00:04:52,650
Not only Henri Pirenne but also Lewis Mumford focused on this culture of city

57
00:04:52,650 --> 00:04:56,110
in pre-modern times.

58
00:04:56,110 --> 00:05:01,530
And also in the field of sociology Gideon Sjoberg

59
00:05:01,530 --> 00:05:07,575
discussed about pre-industrial city because he criticized the Chicago

60
00:05:07,575 --> 00:05:10,900
School of Sociology because Chicago School only

61
00:05:10,900 --> 00:05:13,720
focused on the industrial city, but there

62
00:05:13,720 --> 00:05:18,190
are many different type of city in the world.

63
00:05:18,190 --> 00:05:24,340
So we already discussed about the correspondence,

64
00:05:24,340 --> 00:05:28,980
or the kinds of similarities between pre-industrial city

65
00:05:28,980 --> 00:05:33,440
and post-industrial city.

66
00:05:33,440 --> 00:05:40,590
This similarity also can be extended towards a discussion

67
00:05:40,590 --> 00:05:44,490
about the creative city.

68
00:05:44,490 --> 00:05:50,610
Richard Florida and Charles Landry, some of the sociologists

69
00:05:50,610 --> 00:05:58,840
and some of the scholar emphasized the element of tolerance in creative city.

70
00:05:58,840 --> 00:06:05,940
So more and more in the 21st century, the metropolis or global city

71
00:06:05,940 --> 00:06:15,960
has such kinds of elements of creative cities in Tokyo and some other areas.

72
00:06:15,960 --> 00:06:25,820
Through these kinds of discussions, city can be defined in three different ways.

73
00:06:25,820 --> 00:06:31,360
Firstly, city can be defined as a place of the concentration

74
00:06:31,360 --> 00:06:34,260
of the heterogeneous population.

75
00:06:34,260 --> 00:06:37,240
This is the definition by Chicago School.

76
00:06:37,240 --> 00:06:40,750
But at the same time, city can be defined

77
00:06:40,750 --> 00:06:45,190
as collective consumption, the place of collective consumption

78
00:06:45,190 --> 00:06:49,910
and particular cultural life style.

79
00:06:49,910 --> 00:06:52,200
Some of the critic against the Chicago School

80
00:06:52,200 --> 00:06:57,090
emphasized this dimension of the city.

81
00:06:57,090 --> 00:07:04,110
But on the other hand, I also emphasized, or again emphasize

82
00:07:04,110 --> 00:07:06,810
the importance of concentration.

83
00:07:06,810 --> 00:07:10,970
But concentration of media and public spaces,

84
00:07:10,970 --> 00:07:20,310
or concentration of the many settings of relationship or mediation.

85
00:07:20,310 --> 00:07:24,240
So I've been discussed about such kinds of relationship

86
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:32,160
of gazing, or visualizing relationship in Tokyo in many different ways.

87
00:07:32,160 --> 00:07:41,850
So as a whole, we can define the city which has two different dimensions,

88
00:07:41,850 --> 00:07:44,740
or levels of concentration.

89
00:07:44,740 --> 00:07:48,690
On the one hand, city is a place of the concentration

90
00:07:48,690 --> 00:07:53,910
of the people because my migrants, immigrants, and many other people

91
00:07:53,910 --> 00:07:57,580
come to the city from countryside and foreign countries.

92
00:07:57,580 --> 00:08:02,880
And they built up a kind of community in the city.

93
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:09,180
But people in the city are watching and watched in many different ways.

94
00:08:09,180 --> 00:08:12,610
In some or other places.

95
00:08:12,610 --> 00:08:21,430
So city also can be defined as a stage of self, city is a place of visuality,

96
00:08:21,430 --> 00:08:25,100
so the relationship between these two different type,

